Size: max. pres. length:  0.02620m; max. pres. width:  0.02307m; max. pres. thickness:  0.00380m
Condition: Fragment is broken on four edges.  Oxidized and corroded.
Description: A trapezoidally shaped fragment of bronze vessel preserving two finished sides, both of which have incised decoration. On the very slightly concave side near the narrow end of the trapezoid shape are three incised lines.  Two of them are parallel to one another and almost parallel to the break edges which form the top and bottom of the trapezoid shape. The first line is 0.01191m in length and 0.00132m.  0.00208m away from the first line is the second line which is 0.01080m in length and 0.00099m in width.  The third line corners with the second and projects from it at an approximately thirty degree angle.  The third line is 0.00711m in length and 0.00088m in width.  On the slightly convex side there are incisions along both the top and bottom break edges of the trapezoidal shape.  At the wider end of the trapezoid are  four incisions.  One angles down from the break edge forming the side of the trapezoid shape to the bottom of the trapezoid for a length of 0.01201m; it has a width of 0.00103m.  In the opposite corner of the wide edge of the trapezoid shape are three incised lines.  The first is at a slight angle in relation to the break edge forming the bottom of the trapezoid with a length of 0.00411m and a width of 0.00132m.  The second line corners with the first and projects from it at an approximately thirty degree angle for a length of 0.00621m; it is 0.00059m in width.  A third line, 0.00321m from the second, parallel to the second line is 0.01008m long and 0.00072m wide.  At the narrow end of the trapezoidal shape are two incised lines.  The first is roughly parallel to the break edge forming the top of the narrow end of the trapezoid.  It is 0.01152m in length and 0.00079m in width.  The second line projects from the first at a roughly thirty degree angle for a length of 0.00773m and is 0.00060m wide.

Description: A fragment of bronze fibula of the leech type preserving a portion of the catch plate and portion of the leech body.  The catch plate has an irregular trapezoidal shape, with max. pres. length of 0.01443m, max. pres. height of 0.00781m, min. pres. height of 0.00372m, and max. pres. thickness of 0.00155m.  The exterior of the catch plate is smoothly finished and curving in a convex fashion.  The interior is more corroded and concavely curving in an almost  U  shape.  From the max. pres. height edge of the catch plate, the fragment comes up into the partially preserved leech shaped body (the point of connection is the max. pres. thickness).  The interior of the leech body is broken in such a way to reveal that it has a convex, hollow interior with a somewhat oval shape which tapers towards the point of connection.  The exterior of the fragmentary leech body has nine lines preserved which are roughly parallel to one another and cut across the leech in a perpendicular fashion to the now broken edges.  Max. pres. length of a line:  0.00798m, min. pres. length of a line:  0.00253m, and distance between two lines about 0.00078m.

Creator: Anthony Tuck
Size: Max. Pres. Length 0.054 m, Max. Pres. Length of Catchplate 0.016 m, Max. Pres. Length of Shaft 0.037 m, Max. Pres. Diameter of Coil 0.007 m
Condition: Light and dark green corrosion is visible upon the surface as well as patches of brown.  Fibula is intact except for the pin which is missing.
Description: The preserved portion of the fibula consists of three segments, the catchplate, the bow, and the spring, with only the pin missing.  The catchplate attaches to the bow at its widest point and tapers to a squared terminal end.  The bow is round in section at the attachment point to the catchplate and rounds to the bow.  The upper portion of the bow is roughly diamond shaped in section and displays an incised decorative scheme.  The decoration consists of a series of opposed diagonals meeting a mutual apexes.  At the juncture of the upper set of diagonals, a series of striated lines spans the upper portion of the bow, terminating with a second set of opposed diagonals above the spring.  The spring consists of three coils of narrowing aperture.

Size: max. pres. length of ribbon:  0.05312m; max. pres. width of ribbon:  0.00991m; max. pres. thickness of ribbon:  0.00139m; max. pres. diameter of rivet head:  0.01028m; max. pres. diameter of rivet shaft:  0.00451m; max. pres. height of rivet:  0.00486m
Condition: Fragment is broken and slightly bent at two ends.  Heavily oxidized and encrusted with some corrosion particularly along the curving edges.  The fragment is flaking with many associated flakes saved with it.
Description: A fragment of curving bronze ribbon with two rivets punched through the width of the ribbon.  Both faces of the ribbon appear to be finished.  The concave curve of the ribbon also appears to be finished, while the convex curve may have been finished but is too corroded to tell definitively.  On the finished edge with the rivet heads, at one end a triangular portion of the ribbon bends upward at a forty-five degree angle.  A rivet head is located 0.00979m from the edge from which the triangular projection rises.  At the other end, the ribbon is broken along a curved line and the ribbon additionally bends downward at a sloping, obtuse angle.  0.00901m from that edge is the second rivet head.  The portion of ribbon between the two rivet heads is slightly concave; consequently, the reverse side has a slight convexity there.  On the reverse side, the rivet shafts are visible, with the upper element of their diameters appearing to be finished.  Furthermore, portions of a thin, second layer of bronze is patchily preserved around the base of the shafts; it appears to have once been circular and therefore concentric to the rivet shaft with a max. pres. diameter of 0.00197m.

Condition: The coin has a slight bend in it and there is a light amount of encrustation around the lettering on the front and back. In general, the coin is in excellent condition. All the words and images are completely visible.
Description: A small, thin, ovoid coin that depicts the profile of a man, presumably Vittorio Emanuele, with a stylized, short haircut and a goatee and curled mustache. The lettering on one side reads,  VITTORIO EMANUELE II RE D ITALIA  (Vittorio Emanuele II King of Italy). The obverse reads,  1 CENTESIMO 1867  (1 Cent 1867). The lettering is encircled by a Greek-style corn made from two types of plants. One looks like oak and the other like laurel. At the top of the crown is a 5 point star and a small bow ties the base of the crown together.

Creator: Anthony Tuck
Description: A bronze fibula fragment preserving the catchplate.  There are three preserved faces.  One is flat and thickest (max. pres. width) closest to the break edge (though not directly at the break edge) and tapers as it goes towards a terminus.  The terminus is a raised knob max. pres. height of 0.00405m and max. pres. width of 0.00486m.  The flat portion of this face also appears to preserve three concentric circle designs (max. pres. diam. 0.00301m), with one raised ring and one raised dot at the center.  One edge of this face is 0.00135m in thickness and curves around to a trajectory parallel to the face just described for a width of 0.00285m.  This face then projects away 0.00350m from the parallel trajectory in a convex manner.  The edge of this face is 0.00075m in thickness and curves concavely inward, corresponding to the convex shape of the immediately previously described face, until it also parallels the first face described.  This arrangement gives the fragment a width profile which is roughly a  J  shape (or backwards  J  shape, depending on how viewed).  In its length profile, the curved portion of the catchplate slopes inward at approximately a 25 degree angle from the terminus and the break edge of the first described face.

Description: Bronze fragment broken into a triangular shape and preserving the beveled edge of a rim. The rim measures 0.01905m in length and 0.00904m in width. The beveled rim slopes up to a ridged crest on the exterior side measuring 0.00316m and more gradually on the interior side measuring 0.00862m. There are three fully preserved ridges on the crest and two partial ridges on the broken edges of the crest. The three fully preserved ridges are matched by three equal ridges at the carinating line of the beveled edge 0.00316m away from the crest. Here the fragment transitions to the exterior face of the vessel, which is ribbed in correspondence with the ridges of the crest and the carinating line. The ridges are 0.00341m wide and the best preserved rib is 0.01682m in length. The interior face of the fragment is chipped in two roughly circular areas, one significantly larger than the other (measuring 0.00249m in diameter). The broken edges of the fragment measure 0.02107m and 0.02562m.

Creator: Anthony Tuck
Condition: A fragmentary bronze rosette consisting of two joining fragments which preserve slightly less than half of an originally circular rosette. The larger fragment preserves outside curving border and four complete petals with portions of a fifth to the left and a minute piece of a sixth on the right.  The straight break on the side opposite the curving border has occured at the incision separating the last complete petal on the right with the small portion of the final petal next to it and now almost completely lost.  The smaller fragment also preserves a small portion of the curving border and joins the larger fragment on the left.  The rosette itself has apparently been flattened, apparently by some natural disaster, and thus its original height and contours have not been well preserved.  Curving border of larger fragment has suffered extensive chipping along edge.  Bronze itself is slightly encrusted.
Description: Two bronze fragments preserving slightly less than half of a small bronze rosette, probably a funiture applique.  The two fragments joined together preserve four complete, interlocking petals, most of a fifth to the left, and a minute portion of a sixth on the right.  These petals are outlined by incisions, which radiate from a center for the most part now missing.  The tip of each petal is in the form of two adjoining half-circles; the interior of each of these is adorned with a projecting, round stud. Although the rosette has been flattened, the underside shows that each petal and stud were raised on the top surface, giving it a moulded appearance.
Has note:
The Poggio Civitate Excavation Project website originally included this object at this address:
http://www.poggiocivitate.org/catalog/viewartifactcatalog.asp?fid=PC1977003800

Description: A body fragment of a fibula of navicella type preserving also a portion of the spring.  The fragment has two parallel faces, one the convex exterior and the other the concave interior.  Across the length of the fragment the body is narrow, having concave edges which slope gently to widen at the center.  At its widest point across the length the body fragment almost has the shape of a square turned on its corner and with two corners slightly broken away (ancient breaks).  From this widest point across the length of the fragment the body narrows again roughly symmetrically to the opposite side as it moves towards the spring.  The spring preserves one almost complete coil.  The body fragment also appears to be bifurcated or forked along the edge at the spring end.
